                },
                {
                  "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
                  "params": {
                    "question": "<p>In metabolic acidosis, how do the lungs provide compensation?</p>",
                    "answers": [
                      {
                        "text": "<div>By retaining carbon dioxide through hypoventilation</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hypoventilation retains CO\u2082 and would worsen acidosis. This pattern occurs as compensation in metabolic alkalosis, not acidosis.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>By expelling carbon dioxide through hyperventilation</div>",
                        "correct": true,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. In metabolic acidosis, the lungs compensate within minutes by hyperventilating to blow off CO\u2082, thereby raising pH towards normal.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>By increasing bicarbonate reabsorption</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>Bicarbonate reabsorption is a renal (not pulmonary) compensation mechanism that operates over hours to days.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>By secreting bicarbonate into the airways</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lungs do not secrete bicarbonate. Pulmonary compensation works solely by adjusting the rate of CO\u2082 elimination through changes in ventilation.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "overallFeedback": [
                      {
                        "from": 0,
                        "to": 50,
                        "feedback": "In metabolic acidosis, HCO\u2083\u207b falls first. The lungs compensate quickly (minutes) by hyperventilating to expel CO\u2082. The kidneys provide slower compensation (hours to days) by regenerating HCO\u2083\u207b."
                      },
                      {
                        "from": 51,
                        "to": 100,
                        "feedback": "Correct. Respiratory compensation is rapid \u2014 the lungs respond within minutes by hyperventilating to lower pCO\u2082 and partially correct the acidotic pH."
                      }
                    ],
