                {
                  "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
                  "params": {
                    "question": "<p>What does a raised anion gap in metabolic acidosis indicate?</p>",
                    "answers": [
                      {
                        "text": "<div>Excessive bicarbonate loss from the gastrointestinal tract</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>GI bicarbonate loss (e.g., diarrhoea) causes a normal anion gap (hyperchloraemic) metabolic acidosis, not a raised anion gap.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>Accumulation of unmeasured acid metabolites in the blood</div>",
                        "correct": true,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. A raised anion gap indicates added acids such as lactate (lactic acidosis) or ketoacids (diabetic ketoacidosis) that are not accounted for by chloride or bicarbonate.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>Increased chloride retention by the kidneys</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>Chloride retention produces a normal anion gap acidosis. In a raised anion gap, the unmeasured anions are organic acids, not chloride.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      },
                      {
                        "text": "<div>Primary respiratory carbon dioxide retention</div>",
                        "correct": false,
                        "tipsAndFeedback": {
                          "tip": "",
                          "chosenFeedback": "<div>CO\u2082 retention causes respiratory acidosis, not a change in the anion gap. The anion gap is specific to metabolic acid-base disorders.</div>",
                          "notChosenFeedback": ""
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "overallFeedback": [
                      {
                        "from": 0,
                        "to": 50,
                        "feedback": "The anion gap = Na\u207a \u2212 (Cl\u207b + HCO\u2083\u207b). A raised gap means unmeasured anions (lactate, ketoacids) have replaced bicarbonate. Common causes include DKA, lactic acidosis, and renal failure."
                      },
                      {
                        "from": 51,
                        "to": 100,
                        "feedback": "Well done. A raised anion gap (normal 8\u201312 mEq/L) points to added acid metabolites \u2014 think of diabetic ketoacidosis, lactic acidosis, uraemia, and toxic ingestions."
                      }
                    ],
